User: String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("Hello");
if (s1 == s2) {
    System.out.println("Match");
}
Assistant: This compares two strings.

**Analysis:**
In Java, `==` compares object references (memory addresses). Since `s2` is created with `new`, it has a different memory address than the literal `s1`. You must use `.equals()` to compare the actual content.

**Fixed Code:**
```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("Hello");
if (s1.equals(s2)) {
    System.out.println("Match");
}
```

